8:
What can I say? These vagabond bolts
are longing to stray. I'll be gone before
the year is out... I'm sorry, l'autre moi.
13:
Save the apologies. Don't you think I can
sympathize with "my" feelings? This
planet's too small... Especially for a big
dreamer like "me."
15:
Wouldn't it be grand if we could craft
not only the frame, but also the heart
itself?
18:
We mimicked desire from the humans...
It's a deep emotion, that centuries of
philosophizing couldn't even begin to
crack. Hacking it... That's out of the
question.
21:
And, l'autre moi... Even if it were possible,
would "I" do it? Would "I" change myself
for the world?
25:
I know, I know... Just some idle
speculation. Can't have the sweet
without the bitter, can't have the joy
without the longing.
28:
That's more like it. Since when have "I"
ever had doubts?
30:
Go on then. Keep "my" head high, and
don't look back.
39:
That's right. I know it seems sudden,
but I've come to say my farewells.
40:
And to you, Alk my friend, I wanted to
say sorry. I never did repay the huge
debt I owe you.
43: That's not what I'm worried about here...
49:
It's the region stretching far beyond
what's visible to the naked eye. Skies
light-years and light-years away.
56:
It is a place even further than the stars
you see at night... Is that easier
to comprehend?
59:
The scale is hard to grasp... But
I understand at least that it will be
a long journey.
61:
Yes. The odyssey will span centuries,
at least.
67: Centuries?! You won't rust, will you?
69:
Droids can leap from one body to
another. And as to the rusting of the
mind—the loneliness, the monotony—
why, all I have to do is sleep.
71:
L'autre moi filched me a copy of 
Nexus's system. As long as I've got the 
parts, I can travel on into infinity.
74: But... We will never see each other again.
77:
And I'll miss you terribly, my dear
friends. But it's time that we parted.
80:
I only ask that sometimes, when you
look up at the night sky, you imagine
me there... playing among the stars.
85:
I can't believe he's gone already.
Can we still see him?
89:
No. The sky you're gazing at now is only
an image reflected on a screen.
A wall to shut out fear, danger...
the unexpected.
93:
And, at any rate, "I'd" be on the other
side of the Milky Way by now.
97:
What kind of people do you think live
out there?
100:
Since the dawn of civilization, we've
never once discovered life in the great
unknown.
101:
It's beautiful, isn't it? When you stand
here with your feet on the ground and
your eyes on the stars? But when you're
in space, that's when you realize it's
nothing but a dark void filled with balls
of gas.
104:
The emptiness is terrifying... It may be
why humans built the World Flipper.
To not have to face it all.
108:
And still, the other Regis chose to make
the journey.
110:
He said that somewhere out there,
there may be other travelers that
departed from this planet.
114: My, my. Did "I" really say that?
117:
There might be survivors—humans
that escaped before the fires consumed
everything. And if, by some miracle,
they should meet...
118:
He said they would have a lot to catch
up on.
125:
...We packed a few of our diva's songs
on that ship.  Maybe they'll touch some
beating hearts, even out there in space.
130:
And wouldn't that be something?
Right, Administrator? Wouldn't that
be something...
